text: A sentence is a unit that contains a complete thought. The word the directs a listener's attention to a particular object, and the word and connects units of thoughts in a sentence to each other. Creating this game has made me reflect on these linguistic concepts by considering how they could be represented visually and mechanically. Although I don't know much about linguistics, I use words constantly to transfer information and meaning from me to those that I speak to. It kind of seems that I'm unable to move beyond words as my primary tool of communications. And in art such as games, non-verbal techniques like visual, audio, haptic and interactive elements are creatively used everywhere to form messages and meanings that can't so easily be conveyed through words. Which enables art to talk about things that we otherwise can't. So perhaps I am not really an artist since I keep restricting myself to using words to convey meaning. Now here in this game, instead of turning to alternative, communicative techniques, it's almost as though I'm doubling down on the use of words, trying to add more weight to them by shoving them in your face and forcing you to understand their meaning so that you can interact with them in the correct way. But it's tough to do so, however, and like this section took me about three months to finish because I didn't have many hours in a week to spend on the project. And if I keep adding complexity to this voice to game generator that I'm building here, then every section is going to take more and more time to complete. Maybe I need to scope this project down somehow.
